05309nam a22006615i 9781501761980DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017619807 a10.1515/97815017619802doi  a(DE-B1597)584759  a(OCoLC)1338018476  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE908b.K38 2023 7aHIS0360702bisacsh04a973.9320922231 aKaufman, Burton I., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBarack Obama :bConservative, Pragmatist, Progressive /cBurton I. Kaufman. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (392 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Roots -- t2. From Organizer to Politician -- t3. The Presidential Run and the Earthquake of Iowa -- t4. From Iowa to President-Elect -- t5. Landmark Achievement: The Affordable Care Act -- t6. Quest for a Common Purpose -- t7. The Comeback President -- t8. Dysfunctional Government -- t9. A Second Recovery -- t10. The Shock of Donald J. Trump’s Election -- t11. The Postpresidency -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this insightful biography, Burton I. Kaufman explores how the political career of Barack Obama was marked by conservative tendencies that frustrated his progressive supporters and gave the lie to socialist fearmongering on the right. Obama's was a landmark presidency that paradoxically, Kaufman shows, resulted in few, if any, radical shifts in policy. Following his election, President Obama's supporters and detractors anticipated radical reform. As the first African American to serve as president, he reached the White House on a campaign promise of change. But Kaufman finds in Obama clear patterns of classical conservativism of an ideological sort and basic policy-making pragmatism. His commitment to usher in a multiracial, multiethnic, and multicultural society was fundamentally connected to opening up, but not radically altering, the existing free enterprise system. The Affordable Care Act, arguably President Obama's greatest policy achievement, was a distillation of his complex motivations for policy. More conservative than radical, the ACA fitted the expansion of health insurance into the existing system. Similarly, in foreign policy, Obama eschewed the use of force to affect regime change. Yet he kept boots on the ground in the Middle East and supported ballot-box revolts geared toward achieving in foreign countries the same principles of liberalism, free enterprise, and competition that existed in the United States. In estimating the course and impact of Obama's full political life, Kaufman makes clear that both the desire for and fear of change in the American polity affected the popular perception but not the course of action of the forty-fourth US president.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American politiciansvBiography. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aPresidentszUnited States. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aHISTORY / United States / 21st Century.2bisacsh  aObama political positions, Barack Obama economic conservatism, Obama post-presidency, Obama speeches and interviews, Obama foreign policy, Affordable care act, Barack Obama biography.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075182608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is par